ACT:-DOWRY (SECTION-4)

‚ùì Q1: What is the punishment for demanding dowry under the Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961?
‚úÖ Answer:
As per Section 4 of the Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961, if any person demands dowry, whether directly or indirectly, they shall be:

Punishable with imprisonment for a term not less than six months, which may extend up to two years.
Liable for a fine up to ten thousand rupees.
However, the court has the discretion to impose a lesser punishment if adequate special reasons are recorded in the judgment.
‚ùì Q2: Who can be punished for demanding dowry under Section 4 of the Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961?
‚úÖ Answer:
Under Section 4 of the Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961, the following persons can be punished for demanding dowry:

Parents of the bride or groom.
Relatives of either party.
Guardian of the bride or bridegroom.
Any other person who demands dowry directly or indirectly.
‚ùì Q3: Can a court impose a reduced sentence for demanding dowry?
‚úÖ Answer:
Yes. As per Section 4 of the Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961, the court may impose a sentence of less than six months if it provides adequate special reasons in its judgment.
