ACT:-COPYRIGHTS(SECTION-51)

‚ùì Q1: When is copyright considered to be infringed under The Copyright Act, 1957?
‚úÖ Answer:
As per Section 51 of The Copyright Act, 1957, copyright is deemed to be infringed when a person:

Uses the work without a valid license granted by the copyright owner or the Registrar of Copyrights.
Contravenes any conditions of the granted license.
Engages in unauthorized communication of the work to the public for profit.
Sells, hires, or displays for sale an infringing copy.
Imports infringing copies of the copyrighted work into India, except for personal and domestic use.
‚ùì Q2: Does unauthorized public communication of copyrighted work constitute infringement?
‚úÖ Answer:
Yes. Under Section 51 of The Copyright Act, 1957, if a person communicates a copyrighted work to the public for profit without permission from the copyright owner, it constitutes copyright infringement, unless:

The person was not aware or had no reasonable grounds to believe that the communication would infringe copyright.
‚ùì Q3: Does importing an infringing copy of a work into India always count as copyright infringement?
‚úÖ Answer:
No. As per Section 51 of The Copyright Act, 1957, importing infringing copies into India is generally considered infringement. However, an exception applies:

If a person imports only one copy of a work for personal or domestic use, it does not count as copyright infringement.
